{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2026-04-20T18:50:13.399635+00:00", "modified": "2026-04-22T16:03:33.359746+00:00", "id": 19669163, "conceptrecid": "19669162", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19669163", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.19669162", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.19669163", "metadata": {"title": "Automated Acoustic Species Identification of  European Bats using Variational Bayesian  Non-Parametric Prediction", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19669163", "publication_date": "2012", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) Species identification is a major task in conservation and ecology. In some cases, identification based on acoustic data could be suitable and highly valuable, as well as having the ability to be automated. This work addresses the feature construction methods that can be used to represent bat echolocation calls, which are known to contain species-specific information. Traditionally, callparameters are extracted from calls' spectrograms to summarise the relevant information. Alternative methods could automate this process, such as the spectrogram dissimilarity methods considered here. These methods were compared by utilising supervised learning and classifying 447 echolocation calls from twelve European Myotis species that are commonly di cult to identify acoustically, into six classes. Comparison with an existing classifier revealed the influence of class sizes but also the dangers of over-fitting the species classes when comparing feature construction methods and classifiers. The classes used in this work were tailored to the call-parameter features employed in an existing classification study but the dissimilarity features tested here, a linear cosine dissimilarity method and a Dynamic Time Warping method, did not group the species by similarity into the same groupings. Hence, the call-parameter features out-performed both the cosine and DTW feature construction methods, but the results are encouraging, and would be more successful if they were to be used with di erent classes.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Mroz, Kim", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/e16111e98990712761d928ccc48b7a0e", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/15e5de0fa7fdac6281a75c0591fd8eb4e3920f1df9caa488d84b8dfcc7b00da8", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/5435545/items/M6I4ZRLQ", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/5435545/items/M6I4ZRLQ", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://linker.bio/cut:hash://md5/c7f1cf817322f72fe893c6a60f1b98a4!/b339023-341285", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://md5/0157e8ec3f1f8eb877e7b6cd6fde26bc", "relation": "isPartOf", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.1410543", "relation": "isCompiledBy", "resource_type": "software", "scheme": "doi"}], "custom": {"dwc:class": ["Mammalia"], "dwc:kingdom": ["Animalia"], "dwc:order": ["Chiroptera"], "dwc:phylum": ["Chordata"]}, "resource_type": {"title": "Other", "type": "publication", "subtype": "other"}, "alternate_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/e16111e98990712761d928ccc48b7a0e"}, {"identifier": "urn:lsid:zotero.org:groups:5435545:items:M6I4ZRLQ"}], "communities": [{"id": "batlit"}, {"id": "biosyslit"}], "relations": {"version": [{"index": 0, "is_last": true, "parent": {"pid_type": "recid", "pid_value": "19669162"}}]}}, "title": "Automated Acoustic Species Identification of  European Bats using Variational Bayesian  Non-Parametric Prediction", "links": {"self": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/19669163", "self_html": "https://zenodo.org/records/19669163", "preview_html": "https://zenodo.org/records/19669163?preview=1", "doi": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.19669163